# ⚙️ Installation & Setup

### Step 1 — Update the System

```bash
sudo apt update
sudo apt upgrade
```

---

### Step 2 — Install Snort

```bash
sudo apt install snort -y
```

During installation, Snort asks for **HOME_NET configuration**.

Example:

```
192.168.1.0/24
```

---

# 💻 Commands Used

```bash
# Check Snort version
snort -V

# Identify network interface
ip a

# Run Snort in IDS mode
sudo snort -A console -q -c /etc/snort/snort.conf -i eth0
```

| Option     | Purpose                    |
| ---------- | -------------------------- |
| -A console | Display alerts on terminal |
| -q         | Quiet mode                 |
| -c         | Specify configuration file |
| -i         | Network interface          |

---

# 🧩 Configuration

Main configuration file:

```
/etc/snort/snort.conf
```

Open configuration file:

```bash
sudo nano /etc/snort/snort.conf
```

Define local network:

```
ipvar HOME_NET 192.168.1.0/24
```

---

# 🧠 Custom Rule Creation

Local rule file:

```
/etc/snort/rules/local.rules
```

Example rule to detect **ICMP Ping traffic**:

```
alert icmp any any -> $HOME_NET any (msg:"Ping Detected"; sid:1000001; rev:1;)
```

This rule generates an alert whenever ping traffic is detected.

---

# 🏗️ Snort Architecture

Snort works using several core components:

### 1️⃣ Packet Decoder

Captures network packets from the interface.

### 2️⃣ Preprocessors

Prepare and normalize traffic before inspection.

Examples include:

* Fragmentation handling
* Protocol normalization
* Packet reassembly

### 3️⃣ Detection Engine

Matches network traffic against rule signatures.

### 4️⃣ Logging & Alert System

Stores alerts when suspicious activity is detected.

### 5️⃣ Output Modules

Saves logs into files or monitoring systems.

